Interior_Summary: Little information about interior was gleaned from the investigations, but Kenyon suggested that occupation of the site was similar to that found at Sutton Walls and Dinedor Camp. Internal quarry scoops, especially on the N and S sides
Interior_Surface_Comments: Little information is available from surface evidence, but there are internal quarry scoops, especially on the N and S sides.

Interior_Summary: None
A number of cloudy blue flints, two burnt flints and a core come from the W rampart, otherwise no evidence.

Possible hut circles 12m-15m in diameter were found in the interior. Excavations proved extensive Roman occupation with possible hut circles in interior. This involved Roman occupation of Neronian date with military granary, officer's quarters and commandant's house and trenches of timber buildings cut into the rock. Large pits also found. Pottery and coins of Neronian date (AD 55-60), including 14 sherds of Samian ware of same date. High status finds in area considered as commandant's quarters. Iron Age iron and bronze buckle. Malvernian Iron Age pottery and Cheshire VCP. Plano-convex flint knife from ring ditch.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Possible hut circles 12m-15m in diameter were found in the interior.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Roman occupation of Neronian date with military granary, officer's quarters and commandant's house and trenches of timber buildings cut into the rock. Large pits also found. Numerous postholes attributed to Iron Age occupation. Evidence of roundhouse near NW rampart. Possible Bronze Age ring ditch at highest point of interior.

Interior_Summary: At least 118 hut platforms have been identified in the Phase II enclosure. Quarry hollows also found on the hillfort.
Interior_Water_Comments: Possible spring within the bottom of the first phase ditch. Spring 0.25km outside hillfort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: At least 118 hut platforms have been identified in the Phase II enclosure. Quarry hollows also found on the hillfort.

Interior_Summary: Site destroyed, now only a cropmark and any internal features not recorded.

Interior surface possibly levelled. Coin of Lucilla in Hereford Museum. 4th century AD Roman ware fragment. Flint scraper of indeterminate date. Lump of iron slag. Boar's tusk fragment, bone fragment (indeterminate) and three snail shells.
Interior_Water_Comments: Long pond sited in the S ditch between the inner and outer ramparts on site; River Wye located 0.3 km outside hillfort.

Interior_Summary: No features apparent, but tree clearance and ploughing unearthed Neolithic implements, including scrapers, burins, and arrowhead of lozenge shape. Also Mesolithic microlith. To W of hillfort ramparts outside the fort quantity of Iron Age pottery, blue glass bead and worn 3rd or 4th century Roman coin found.
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream 0.8 km located outside the hillfort

Interior_Summary: No features apparent and woodland inhibits identification.
None
Interior_Water_Comments: River Teme located 0.3 km outside the hillfort.

Interior_Summary: Quarry hollows on surface. Excavation showed timber granaries, thought by Stanford to be habitation, similar to those found on the Wrekin, Croft Ambrey and Midsummer Hill.
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.6km outside fort. Quarry scoops could have acted as ponds in places.
Interior_Surface_Comments: There are internal quarry scoops around much of the circuit, some used as ponds. Heavy woodland hampers evaluation
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Evidence of timber granaries found. Postholes for corner posts of two sizes - 2.5m sq and 2.5m by 3.5m. Most rebuilt to the same plan six times. Probably four-posters, although Stanford postulated dwellings and the site holding 4,000 people and the political capital of the region. Pits thought late by Stanford, one at least, containing Romano-British pottery (Stanford 1970, 116).

Interior_Summary: Rows of possibly four-posters for grain storage a feature of the excavations. Pit evidence found by excavation (14 pits) in the main enclosure. Most only to just over 1m deep.At least five periods of modification/reconstruction. Terrace and mound constructed in the annexe in the Roman period. Two medieval pillow mounds in the annexe. Platforms protected by drainage hoods on the N side of the quarry ditch. Iron Age and Roman pottery, metal-ware and bone found with many other finds in the excavations.
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.5 km outside the hillfort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Terrace and mound constructed in the annexe in the Roman period. Two medieval pillow mounds in the annexe. Platforms protected by drainage hoods on the N side of the quarry ditch. terraces cut into the N-facing hillside.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Rows of four-post structures and pit evidence found by excavation (14 pits) in the main enclosure. Most less than 1m deep. Some contained burnt clay and grain (carbonised wheat), but only four of suitable depth for grain storage. A Roman terrace and squarish mound found in the annexe. Further detail from the fine excavation report.

Interior_Summary: Heavy occupation proved behind the ramparts as a result of the trial excavation, but none on the crest of the hill. Iron Age pottery, daub, bone, iron fragments, iron axehead and Roman sherds found. Also coins of Galba (AD 68-69) and Citellius. Watching brief on development to E of hillfort showed pit and shallow ditch with mid Iron Age pottery and Roman Severn Valley ware.
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.5 km outside the fort.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Three successive floors found. Heavy occupation proved behind the ramparts as a result of the trial excavation, but none on the crest of the hill. Watching brief on development to E of hillfort showed pit and shallow ditch with mid Iron Age pottery and Roman Severn Valley ware.

Interior_Summary: Antler fragment dated to 1450 BC. Charcoal. Excavation report forthcoming.
Interior_Water_Comments: River Lugg located 0.6 km outside the hillfort.

Interior_Summary: No features known, but chance finds of Neolithic struck flint and Romano-British pottery.
None
Interior_Water_Comments: River Teme runs directly below the site.

Interior_Summary: No known excavation in the interior. Fragments of burnt bone, charcoal found (1985) and quantity of midlle Iron Age stamped Malvernian ware found in ditch, Droitwich VCP, fragments of a crucible, bone, flint and part of a shale object (2012).
Interior_Water_Comments: River Wye/stream located 0.01 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: Univallate site difficult to interpret because of lack of investigation and virtual destruction.
None
Lack of investigation and tree growth inhibits comment.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.2 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: Limestone briquetage, Iron Age pottery and limestone rubble associated with occupation found in 1996 service trench. Row of postholes found along section between two enclosures. Human burials found during limestone quarrying. Good bone survival.
Interior_Water_Comments: Marl Brook located 2.5 km outside hillfort
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Recording of narrow service trench 1996 for 400m, SW from the NE corner to Camp Farm. Shallow gullies, postholes and layers of limestone rubble were found associated with occupation.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Row of postholes found along section between two enclosures found.

Interior_Summary: 30 platforms in 'annexe' and possible hut platforms in main enclosure. Quarry scoops, later barrows and pillow mounds in latter. Several mineshafts in interior, one formally considered a well. The recent excavation details have to be confirmed. Middle Iron Age pottery, Cheshire and Droitwich VCP. Single sherd of possible late Bronze Age/early Iron Age pottery. Bone (incl. die and toggle) and antler objects, charcoal and iron roasting evidence.
Interior_Water_Comments: River Wye located 0.3 km outside the fort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: 30 hut platforms in 'annexe' and possible hut platforms in main enclosure. Quarry scoops, barrows and pillow mounds in latter. Several mineshafts in interior, one formally considered a well.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Two building terraces excavated after middle Iron Age pottery found as a result of beech wind-throw.

Interior_Summary: No archaeology found in interior excavation. Excavation followed geophysical survey - no details.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: No archaeology found in interior excavation.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Excavation followed geophysical survey - no details.

Interior_Summary: A large number of hut platforms recorded during the excavations and as surface features. Pottery and other artefacts from excavations.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring/stream at south gate. Spring 0.4km outside the hillfort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: The large number of hut platforms on the hillside are a feature of the site. Internal quarry ditch around most of the site. Pillow mounds.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: The large number of hut platforms recorded during the excavations are a feature  of the site.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Stanford undertook geophysics on the site. Details not determined.

Interior_Summary: No evidence for interior features. Stray finds of 'duck stamped' pottery from ploughed-down rampart at NE corner. coarse black pottery similar to that from Sutton Walls (Atlas No 0031). Small fragment of Romano-British globular jar from W side of fort.

Main_Display_Name: Pen-Twyn Camp, Brilley, Herefordshire (Pen Twyn Camp)
Interior_Summary: Little is known about the site because of access problems. Access denied for Herefordshire Council survey of 2012.
None

Main_Display_Name: Poston Camp, Herefordshire (Lower Park Wood Camp)
Interior_Summary: Some finds of pottery from the 'Roman layers' and 'ash' (Marshall 1934). Occupation layers found. Quarry hollows.
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.6 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: None other than possible quarry scoops.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.25 km outside the hillfort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Interior steep with no sign of hut platforms, but possible sites in quarry scoops behind rampart

Interior_Summary: Roman pottery.
Interior_Water_Comments: Located on the edge of Holly Brook.

Interior_Summary: The use of the site as a toxic waste dump until the 1980's has precluded surface investigation and interpretation of any features in the interior. The site was particularly rich in finds, with much human and animal bone, including 24 human skeletons, Iron Age and Roman pottery, loom weights, spindle whorls and weaving combs and cheek-pieces of bridles, glass objects and iron and bronze working in general, all show that here was a thriving farming community.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.65 km outside the hillfort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: The use of the site as a quarry and toxic waste dump until the 1980's has precluded surface investigation and interpretation of any features in the interior.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Possible that quarry hollows were used as dwelling sites.

Interior_Summary: Nothing was determined concerning the interior in the trial excavations of 1932 and 1952. Some Roman-British pottery was found in occupation layers. Tip of 'spear head' found in ditch.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.5 km outside the hillfort.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Nothing determined in the trial excavations.

Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: Humber Brook located 0.3 km outside hillfort.

Main_Display_Name: Wall Hills Camp, Ledbury, Herefordshire (Wall Hills, Ledbury)
Interior_Summary: No surface features recorded. Chance finds of the following: fragments of dark grey/black ware, similar to that from British Camp Atlas No 0005) and light red ware, similar to that from Sutton Walls (Atlas No 0031). Some Romano-British sherds. Bronze Roman coins. A number of flint flakes.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.4 km outside the hillfort.

Interior_Summary: None.
None
Three pillow mounds and modern quarry in the interior, otherwise no features recorded.
Interior_Water_Comments: Hindwell Brook located 0.7 km outside the hillfort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Three pillow mounds in the interior. Modern quarry.

Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.2 km outside the hillfort.

Interior_Summary: Interior features possible from excavations probably vestiges of mining activity. No other evidence other than spring on former site. Hillfort destroyed.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Interior features possible from excavations probably vestiges of mining activity.

Interior_Summary: Chance finds of small fragments of Samian ware and black ware found before 1958.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.3 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: No known evidence.
None
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.2 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.2 km outside the hillfort.

Interior_Summary: None
None.

Aerial spraying has revealed hut platforms. Evidence of c. 20 hut platforms in the SE and NW quadrants. Investigation of hut revealed a rock-cut platform and at least two circular hut gullies and postholes.
Interior_Water_Comments: Springs found on site near the NE entrance and at a gap in the third rampart at the SE corner.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Aerial spraying has revealed hut platforms. Evidence of c. 20 hut platforms in the SE and NW quadrants.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Investigation of hut revealed a rock-cut platform and at least two circular hut gullies and postholes.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Resistivity surveys of the inner circuit. No details recorded.

Interior_Summary: Pillow mound and possible post-medieval platform (possible warrener's lodge). Stone quarry on the N side of the interior. Possible quarry scoops in the interior of the innermost rampart. Flint axe.
Interior_Water_Comments: Springs located 0.3 km outside the hillfort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Pillow mound and possible post-medieval platform (possible warrener's lodge). Possible quarry hollows in the interior of the innermost rampart.

Interior_Summary: Rubble walled rectangular building (Roman temple?) at the S end of the central ridge excavated in the 1930's with a room 4.5 m by 8.75 m internally and a smaller part-paved, possible annexe to the N. Also possible hearths in interior (Morris, 1932).  Possible quern and iron object found in 1930's excavations. Possible evidence of roundhouses. Quarry ditches evident.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Quarry ditches evident. Possible roundhouse evidence.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Rectangular building (Roman temple?) at the S end of the central ridge excavated in the 1930's with a room 4.5m by 8.75m internally and a smaller part-paved, possible annexe to the N. Rubble walls, 0.8m-1.45m thick. Also possible hearths in interior (Morris, 1932).
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Topographical and geophysical surveys found a domed interior with extensive Iron Age terracing and revealed a possible cross-ridge dyke as well as roads and circular structures.

Main_Display_Name: Caer Caradoc, Clun, Shropshire (Caer Caradoc, Chapel Lawn; Gaer Ditches)
Interior_Summary: Around six hut platforms visible at the E end of the site. Inner quarry ditch in parts and evidence of hut sites sheltering in the lee of the rampart. Neolithic/Bronze Age worked flints and scrapers found. Small conical pit, 5 m in diameter, in the centre of the site, thought to be a grain storage pit, is probably an old mineral shaft.
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.4 km outside the fort. Collapsed shaft near centre of enclosure could possibly be a well.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Around six hut platforms visible at the E end of the site. Inner quarry ditch in parts and evidence of hut sites sheltering in the lee of the rampart. Small conical pit, 5 m in diameter and 1.3 m deep, in the centre of the site, previously thought to be a grain storage pit, is probably an old mineral shaft.

Interior_Summary: Small terraces and building platforms visible in the SE. Interior divisions may mark zoning in the interior.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring in the NW interior of the site.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Small terraces and building platforms visible in the SE. Interior divisions may mark zoning in the interior.

Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: River Camlad located 0.1 km (100m below) outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: In the interior are level platforms, some partly cut into the slope and spoilheap or midden.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.2 km outside the fort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: In the interior are level platforms, some partly cut into the slope and spoilheap or midden.

Interior_Summary: Possibly a few hut platforms.
Interior_Water_Comments: River Camlad located 0.1km (100m below) outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.7 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: Building platforms recorded in the interior.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Ring, Gorsty Bank, Shropshire (Gorsty Bank)
Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.45 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: River Onny located 0.4km outside the fort.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Hill, Oak Hill, Shropshire (Oak Hill)
Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.65 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.2 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: None

No evidence of occupation is visible in the interior, but many post-holes and unusual semi-circular possible structures found. Paucity of finds, but few sherds of Malvernian and Clee Hills pottery. Some carbonised grain.
Interior_Water_Comments: Ledwyche Brook located 0.3 km outside the hillfort.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Many post-holes and unusual semi-circular possible structures found in the interior.

Interior_Summary: Roman coins and a gold ring set with lapius lazuli, of uncertain date, are the only stray finds from the site.
Bell-pits in interior.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.3 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: None
Interior_Water_Comments: Llyn Rhuddwyn 0.2 km outside the fort.

Interior_Summary: None

Possible hut platforms visible. Small indeterminate excavation on summit 2011 to determine origin of possible gully. Possible evidence of vitrification. Half of an undated bronze ring and flint flakes chance finds, now in Shrewsbury Museum.
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.3 km outside the fort.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Small indeterminate excavation on summit 2011 to determine origin of possible gully.

Interior_Summary: Simms found evidence of a hearth in 1943, but Stanford found no structures in 1977. Quarrying in 1934 found levelled areas quarried into the rock paved with sandstone. In 1997, two small pits were found in the interior. VCP (briquetage) sherds found by Stanford (1977) similar to those found at The Berth and the Wrekin inner camp. Also 20 seeds  of, probably, corn.
Interior_Water_Comments: Pond on site the result of quarrying.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Hearth found by Simms in 1943 and a possible small pit by Stanford in 1977. Quarrying in 1934 found levelled areas quarried into the rock paved with sandstone.

Interior_Summary: Pottery spindle whorl and worked flints as surface finds.
Interior_Water_Comments: Folly Brook located 0.45 km outside the fort.

Main_Display_Name: Haughmond Hill Camp, Shropshire (Haughmond Castle; Castle Earthwork)
Interior_Summary: Possible iron slag evidence of metal working. 18th century folly of Haughmond Castle in interior as are remnants of a WWII spigot mortar emplacement, possibly used by the Home Guard.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located 0.4 km outside the fort and above River Severn.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Quarry depressions in the interior. 18th century folly of Haughmond Castle in interior as are remnants of a WWII spigot mortar emplacement, possibly used by the Home Guard.

Interior_Summary: None

Pipe trench for reservoir 1981 produced hearth, pit and charcoal. Hoard of 33 coins dating between 30 BC and AD 161 from the Ogof. Hollows visible, buts site features much obscured by golf course and uncertain.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Hollows visible, buts site features much obscured by golf course and uncertain.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Pipe trench for reservoir 1981 produced hearth, pit and charcoal.

Interior_Summary: There is surface evidence of a square low platform with possible E entrance in the NW quadrant and a small ditched enclosure to its SW. The latter is certainly a WWII Home Guard site. No evidence of hut platforms.
Interior_Water_Comments: Clee Brook located 0.25km outside the fort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: There is surface evidence of a square low platform with possible E entrance in the NW quadrant and a small ditched enclosure to its SW. The latter is certainly a WWII Home Guard site. No evidence of hut platforms.

Interior_Summary: Small stone quarries in the NW sector (modern?).
Interior_Water_Comments: River Onny is located 0.7km. from the fort. There is a possible spring located 50m from the SE entrance as an oval depression.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Small stone quarries in the NW sector, probably modern.

Interior_Summary: Finds of VCP and evidence of metal working in bronze using copper ore from Llanymeynech Hill. Some evidence of stone-built strutures in the interior.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Evidence of stone-built structures, but no excavation report by Varley to provide detail.

Interior_Summary: Excavation showed no interior features. Several coins and 2nd to 4th century pottery (jars and bowls) found in excavations.
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located 0.7km outside the hillfort. The existence of a modern manhole could indicate an earlier water supply on site.

Interior_Summary: Excavations undertaken by G.H. Smith in 1990 found a cobbled surface at the SW entrance of probable Iron Age date. The limited excavation of the interior showed two curving drip gullies of a possible roundhouse. Partial excavation of the ditches showed it to be c. 2m in depth with a waterlogged base. It is possible that this could indicate an on site water supply.
Interior_Water_Comments: Partial excavation of the ditches showed it to be c. 2m in depth with a waterlogged base. It is possible that this could indicate an on site water supply.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavations undertaken by G.H. Smith in 1990 found a cobbled surface at the SW entrance of probable Iron Age date. Into interior? The limited excavation of the interior showed two curving drip gullies of a possible roundhouse.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Topographical and geophysical surveys determined form and buried features of the site and also showed another possible entrance to the NE as a buried feature.

Interior_Summary: The excavation concentrated on the S defences near to the E of the SW entrance with no interior excavation, as a result there are no indications, as yet, of interior settlement.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: The excavation concentrated on the S defences near to the E of the SW entrance with no interior excavation.

Interior_Summary: None

Main_Display_Name: Ratlinghope Hill Camp, Shropshire (Ratlinghope Hill; Stitt Hill)
Interior_Summary: None

In 1990 a small excavation in advance of farmhouse extension found clay deposits possibly being part of the inner bank, a small curvilinear feature and a post hole. Pottery sherds and a Bronze Age cremation urn with flint flakes were found.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: In 1990 a small excavation in advance of farmhouse extension found clay deposits possibly being part of the inner bank, a small curvilinear feature and a posthole.

Interior_Summary: None
In the centre of the interior a Neolithic hearth and sherd was found, with a perforated hammer stone under the S rampart. The pottery was confirmed as Windmill Hill ware.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Neolithic hearth found in the centre of the site.

Interior_Summary: Two platforms have been cut into the slope on the N side of the larger enclosure and may be of late date. In the smaller enclosure are two platforms cut into the rampart on the S and there is evidence of quarrying here, possibly of ancient date. Gelling found evidence of two timber buildings on the same level NW of the main entrance, one of Iron Age and the other of 4th. century AD date. VCP pottery was found in all layers by Gelling, with mid to late Iron Age and Roman ware in the upper layers. This included a sherd of 'duck stamped' ware, typical of the Welsh Marches, and sherds of linear and scored ware and several Roman sherds. VCP made up three-quarters of the pottery found. Metalware included iron knives and a La Tene brooch. Earlier, before 1906, a bronze cauldron of sub-Roman to Roman date, had been found and a Romano-British glass bead was found in 1976.
Interior_Water_Comments: It is possible that the causeways could have been used to retain water. The site was surrounded by adequate water sources of fen and pools.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Two platforms have been cut into the slope on the N side of the larger enclosure and may be of late date. In the smaller enclosure are two platforms cut into the rampart on the S and there is evidence of quarrying here, possibly of ancient date.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Gelling found evidence of two timber buildings on the same level NW of the main entrance, one of Iron Age and the other of 4th. century AD date.

Main_Display_Name: The Burgs, Shropshire (The Buries; Bayston Hill)
Interior_Summary: Much affected by development and no interior evidence as result.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Interior not excavated, but features can be expected.

Main_Display_Name: The Ditches, Mogg Forest, Shropshire (Larden Ditches; Mogg Ditches; The Rings; Wynbury Castle; Larden Castle)
Interior_Summary: None
None
Hut platform visible 7.5m in diameter.
Interior_Water_Comments: Stream located downslope 0.2km from the fort.

Interior_Summary: Towards the N end of the site a possible hut platform is visible, scooped out of the E-facing slope and measuring 11m by 7m. No other sign of activity can be seen.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located downslope 0.5km outside the fort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Towards the N end of the site a possible hut platform is visible, scooped out of the E-facing slope and measuring 11m by 7m. No other sign of activity can be seen.

Interior_Summary: Excavations in 1939 and 1973, the latter in advance of the construction of a television mast, found post-built structures (with three to four rebuilding phases) and hearths set into the hillside and possible storage pits. Late Bronze Age pottery of 9th-8th centuries  BC suggest an early origin to the fort, in keeping with other major Marches sites such as Y Breiddin, which is visible from The Wrekin. Late Bronze Age pottery (c. 9th-8th centuries BC) and two Roman javelin heads. found.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavations in 1939 and 1973, the latter in advance of the construction of a television mast, found post-built structures (with three to four rebuilding phases) and hearths set into the hillside and possible storage pits. Late Bronze Age pottery of 9th-8th centuries  BC suggest an early origin to the fort, in keeping with other major Marches sites such as Y Breiddin, which is visible from The Wrekin.

Interior_Summary: There are two ring cairns in the W quarter and possible, but undefined, evidence of occupation in the interior. Very small fragments of flint and possible pounders or sling stone.
Interior_Water_Comments: Bensons Brook is located 0.3km outside the hillfort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: There are two ring cairns in the W quarter and possible, but undefined, evidence of occupation in the interior.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Undefined, evidence of occupation in the interior.

Main_Display_Name: Wall Camp, Kynnersley, Shropshire (The Wall; Kinnersley Wall)
Interior_Summary: Limited excavation of the interior in 1983 close to Wall Farm, which stands in the centre of the fort, however, found circular and rectangular post-built structures. Iron Age pottery and VCP from the brine springs of Cheshire.
Interior_Water_Comments: Strine Book borders site, but an abundance of water sources surrounding the site in prehistory.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Limited excavation of the interior in 1983 close to Wall Farm, which stands in the centre of the fort, however, found circular and rectangular post-built structures.

Interior_Summary: A geophysical survey of 1999, although being generally inconclusive, found remnants of the inner bank in several places in the interior.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: A geophysical survey of 1999, although being generally inconclusive, found remnants of the inner bank in several places in the interior.

Interior_Summary: None
No contemporary features have been investigated within the interior and nothing is known
Interior_Water_Comments: A location of a number of springs are shown by Wood (1959; Fig 2) in the north-east and south. A well in the S is reputed never to run dry
Interior_Surface_Comments: Quarrying has caused some damage to the bank in the south-west and within the interior.  Some WWII activity

Main_Display_Name: Bussock Camp, West Berkshire (Bussock Wood Camp)
Interior_Summary: The hillfort is now wooded and interior features are unknown. Calcined flints and possible pot-boilers found during an excursion of the Newbury District Field Club (1872-5)
No surface features are visible although a pit was briefly excavated by Crawford in 1907
Interior_Water_Comments: Alleged dew pond within the interior, possibly originating from a chalk pit, said to never run dry
Interior_Surface_Comments: Pits in the western sector appear to be the result of chalk digging. The interior of the hillfort has been extensively cultivated.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Small pit briefly excavated by O.G.S. Crawford
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: In the region of 60 percent of the hillfort interior has been surveyed (Payne, 2006: 44-7).  Very few archaeological features could be identified and it is thought that the underlying geology rendered the survey difficult to analyse, although it was also suggested that the hillfort saw only low-level activity.

Interior_Summary: Mostly destroyed, no evidence for interior features
Interior_Water_Comments: A number of springs rise in the area

Interior_Summary: Unexcavated, but chance finds of possible Iron Age pottery 1977, 1980 and 1987 and Neolithic chipped and polished grey flint axe and Neolithic or later grey flint adze or chisel, both in Passmore Collection, Ashmolean Museum, Oxford. In S interior possible hut circle c. 12m diameter showing as cropmark.
Interior_Surface_Comments: In S interior possible hut circle c. 12m diameter showing as cropmark.

Interior_Summary: Excavation shows at least one roundhouse and two lines of stones 30m long and 90cm apart which have been interpreted as hearths. Surface evidence - a low, stone walled enclosure is undated but possibly contemporary with the enclosure.

The interior was deep ploughed during World War II and there is no surface evidence for intensive settlement. 32 sherds of Early Iron Age Pottery were recovered from plough soil in the 1930s; a few more were recovered in the 1960s.  Possible quarry hollows. Pits shown by geophysical survey.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Five circular hollows are probably marl pits.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Approximately 100 positive anomolies suggest probable pits and lengths and ditch.  The density and clustering of pits is similar to tthat seen at other local hillforts where occupation was short-lived and restricted to the early Iron Age (Payne et al. 2006)

Interior_Summary: Very little activity has been recorded, possible road/track by geophysics, surface finds.
Interior_Water_Comments: A well is shown on the 1:25,000 1937-61 OS map

In S angle of the enclosure three bowl barrows between inner rampart and internal lynchet. Pits found, some intersecting each other, containing early Iron Age pottery, animal remains, quernstones, metalwork and iron hoops (parts of chariot wheel). Rescue work carried out by Ministry of Works in 1957 also recovered Iron Age pottery. Roman finds, mainly coins, found plough layer within interior, but no Roman features recorded during the excavations. An Iron Age inhumation cemetery near the NW entrance. Several human skeletons, skulls and part of a horse skeleton have been found at various times.  Aerial Photographs suggest possible field system in interior.
Interior_Surface_Comments: In S angle of the enclosure three bowl barrows between inner rampart and internal lynchet.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Nine storage pits found by Cunnington 1922. Partial excavation in the 1950's revealed traces of postholes and pits. An inhumation cemetery near the NW entrance. In S angle of the enclosure three bowl barrows between inner rampart and internal lynchet. Partial excavations in the 19th century produced a primary cremation and two secondary skeletons in one, a cremation in another and no finds in the other, its status being questioned.

Interior_Summary: Two small excavations with no details. Geophysical survey showed considerable interior features, many probably prehistoric. Six sub-surface hut circles to add to the 35 surface identified. Former possibly earlier occupation. Few chance finds dateable to early or middle Iron Age. Military digging 1939-45 exposed early and middle Iron Age pottery. "Blacksmith's' hoard of iron tools found in 19th century previously dated to 200-50BC by MacGregor and Simpson (1963) now thought to be late Roman votive deposit.
Interior_Surface_Comments: One slight mound may indicate barrow cemetery outside to W may have extended into fort. 35 hut circles to add to six from geophysical survey.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Two small excavations with no details.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Wessex Hillforts Project survey found considerable interior features, many probably prehistoric. Six sub-surface hut circles to add to the 35 surface identified. Former possibly earlier occupation. Many pits suggesting long period of occupation.

Interior_Summary: Quarry scoop traces. Geophysical surveys showed large roundhouse and four large circular depressions in the interior plus a few pits. The excavation, yielded Romano-British and Roman-type  5th-6th AD century pottery with a few later sherds. During flint digging in the NE interior, 1896-1900, Iron Age objects collected including bronze awl, bronze ear-ring, pottery, saddle quern fragments, spindle whorls, possible part of iron bucket. Also chance finds of Bronze Age, early Iron Age and Romano-British pottery.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Very partial excavation in interior. No evidence found for battle of Mount Badon.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Geophysical surveys showed very large roundhouse of c. 18m diameter and four large circular depressions in the interior, plus  pits and curving ditches or gullies, with concentration on N and W parts of enclosure.

Interior_Summary: Pits. Middle to late Iron Age 'bead-rim' pottery. Human remains, including skulls. Spindle whorls and loom weights, quern pieces, slingstones, hammerstones and oyster shells. Iron objects, including tools. Roman coins from Claudius I (AD 41-54) to Constantine II (AD 317-337) and other Roman items, including Samian ware fragment. Late Bronze Age metalwork, including palstave and bronze stud found in immediate vicinity of hillfort.
Interior_Water_Comments: Enclosure sweeps down into shallow combe on S where  entrance sited with spring nearby. Unusual plan of site seems to favour stock control downslope to spring.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Cunningtons' excavations referred to pits excavated as 'pit dwellings'. Also T-shaped 'hypercaust' hearths on side of ditch.

Interior_Summary: No interior details from excavation. Neolithic flint flakes and tools. Early and middle Iron Age pottery. Sherd of late Bronze Age Plain Ware and 11 sherds of haematite-coated pottery of All Cannings Cross tradition. Possible Mesolithic flaked axe found 1969.
Finds from Steel's excavation, including pre-Roman and New Forest pottery, and parts of two iron bow-fibulae in Salisbury Museum.

Rampart only seen on APs in N and E. Internal quarry scoops located immediately within the rampart, best seen to S. Possible building platforms. Field system and boundary banks. Five human skeletons deposited in chalk filling of rampart when built at time rampart built found by P.F. Ewence with early Iron Age sherd. Late Iron Age sherd found by R.S. Newall on ploughed land at the edge of hillfort.
Interior_Water_Comments: Dew-pond c.16 sq m area 10m to W of the hillfort. Surrounded by low bank.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Internal quarry scoop located immediately within the rampart, best seen to S. Possible building platforms. Field system and boundary banks.

Interior_Summary: Iron Age sherds and two flint scrapers found 1898. Shallow quarry hollows.

Great intensity of occupation with over 130 probable structures surviving mainly as hollows up to 1m deep. Majority circular, 7m to 15m diameter, many being set within compounds or yards. On N and E, between earlier circuit and inner rampart, large compounds containing structures visible, with possible stone footings visible within many. Not all of these structures likely contemporary. Within a number of them indications of overlapping elements. Also pits, probably contemporary with the occupation, visible. Excavations have recovered Iron Age and Roman pottery, as well as inhumations in both graves and pits, and other human remains. Iron Age and Roman coins were also found. Roman material, including pottery, tiles, coins and burials from excavation and chance finds led to site's inclusion in Scott's gazetteer of Roman villas.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Great intensity of occupation with over 130 probable structures surviving mainly as hollows up to 1m deep. Majority circular, 7m to 15m diameter, many being set within compounds or yards. On N and E, between earlier circuit and inner rampart, large compounds containing structures visible, with possible stone footings visible within many. Not all of these structures likely contemporary. Within a number of them indications of overlapping elements. Also pits, probably contemporary with the occupation, visible. Prominent sheep folds visible, a rectangular area 120m by 90m and consisting of 16 low mounds in two blocks of 8. The present sheep fold probably 19th century. Quarry scoops behind inner rampart for most of circuit.

Interior_Summary: Site regularly photographed since 1940's showing no interior features. Two dark marks in centre of enclosure, recorded on 1945 aerial photographs, may be relatively modern.  Excavation 1800-10 by W. Cunnington Sen. with no evidence of occupation.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavation 1800-10 by W. Cunnington Sen. with no evidence of occupation.

Main_Display_Name: Oldbury Castle, Wiltshire (Oldbury Hill; Oldbury Camp)
Interior_Summary: Magnetometer survey in 1996 revealed an internal ditch dividing N third of hillfort from remainder. Survey revealed ditches, ring gullies and pits. Iron Age pottery, haematite coated ware, loom weights, mullers, weaving comb, querns, metal objects, Roman coins of Domitian-Magnus Maximus. Pits excavated, first 1875 by Cunnington, and others after. Magnetometer survey in 1996 revealed internal ditch dividing the N third of the hillfort from remainder, possibly boundary ditch. In N and E sectors up to 20 faintly visible circular anomalies may indicate positions of round timber buildings defined by outer ring-gullies. Scattered among these structures are more than 150 pits.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Pits excavated, first 1875 by Cunnington, and others after. Magnetometer survey in 1996 revealed internal ditch dividing the N third of the hillfort from remainder, possibly boundary ditch. In N and E sectors up to 20 faintly visible circular anomalies may indicate positions of round timber buildings defined by outer ring-gullies. Scattered among these structures are more than 150 pits.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Magnetometer survey in 1996 revealed an internal ditch dividing N third of hillfort from remainder. Survey revealed ditches, ring gullies and pits.

Interior_Summary: Presumed post-medieval chalk or flint extraction pits.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Presumed post-medieval chalk or flint extraction pits.

Interior_Summary: Two Bronze Age 'hearths' found by Cunningtons 1907. Late Bronze Age, Iron Age and Romano-British wares. Pieces of bronze and iron. Geophysics of interior showed nothing prehistoric.
Interior_Water_Comments: Dew pond in interior. Mother Anthony's Well sited downslope at foot of hill.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: No substantial evidence of interior activity found.

Interior_Summary: Neolithic flint assemblage found as well as uninscribed gold coin, with obverse plain convex; reverse concave, showing a disjointed horse and wheel, probably Iron Age-Romano-British in date.
None
No evidence for internal features.

Pits found along the potential NE entrance. In vicinity of  enclosure number of ditches identified, probably forming part of an associated field system. Finds included two bronze coins of Tetricus I and Constantine II. Many chance finds of burnt flints or 'pot-boilers' occur in profusion and some Iron Age sherds. Base of pot of New Forest Ware now in Salisbury Museum.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Pits found along the potential NE entrance. In vicinity of  enclosure number of ditches identified, probably forming part of an associated field system.

Interior_Summary: Quarry hollows. Possible ovens or corndryers and strikealights found.

Cunnington excavation showed no features. Iron Age sherds found in the rampart on S. Interior divided up by field system, visible on aerial photographs, and in important area for associated field systems, which could be significant in location. Colt Hoare excavation showed no features.

Cunnington excavation within 'plateau' interior. No details of P. Dunn undergraduate survey 2004. Ewart Park late Bronze Age sword and Bronze Age and early Iron Age pottery. Grooved ware and Beaker sherds from excavation of inner ditch. Early Iron Age sherds of All Cannings Cross type including haematite-coated ware.
Interior_Surface_Comments: One theory of inner ditch is quarry hollow. Many irregular 'pits' inside ditch suggest possibly unfinished.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: No details of P. Dunn 2004 undergraduate survey.

Interior_Summary: Excavations in interior found evidence of early Iron Age settlement and of later Iron Age and Romano-British occupation from the 1st to 3rd centuries AD. Excavations by St John Hope in 1911 found Iron Age pit in S. Strap- union horse trapping chance find.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavations in interior found evidence of early Iron Age settlement and of later Iron Age and Romano-British occupation from the 1st to 3rd centuries AD. Excavations by St John Hope in 1911 found Iron Age pit in S.

Interior_Summary: Pottery dating mainly to the 5th century BC, with middle Iron Age types being almost entirely absent. Worked flint and possible Roman tile from watching brief 1996. Geophysical Surveys in 1995 in S part revealed linear anomaly enclosing a semi-circular area approximately 30m in diameter which probably represents a cut, a ditch, a dwelling or a Bronze Age barrow. The hillfort rampart clearly visible. A narrow band may represent a revetment or counterscarp feature. The 1987 excavation also found a post-hole/small pit.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: The 1987 excavation found a posthole/small pit.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Geophysical Surveys in 1995 in the S part of revealed linear anomaly enclosing a semi-circular area approximately 30m in diameter which probably represents a cut, a ditch, a dwelling or a Bronze Age barrow. The hillfort rampart is clearly visible. A narrow band may represent a revetment or counterscarp feature.

Interior_Summary: Parchmarks probably represent position of small pits. Finds included pottery, piece of loom weight, three worked chalk discs, bone counter and human jawbone.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Parchmarks probably represent position of small pits.

Interior_Summary: Internally S half has large number of irregular scoops, not necessarily hut sites, since there has also been flint digging in the area. Late Hallstatt-La Tene sherds (comparable with All Cannings ware) found by Hawkes and Meyrick in fort and nearby.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Internally S half has large number of irregular scoops, not necessarily hut sites, since there has also been flint digging in the area.

Main_Display_Name: Martinsell Hill Camp, Wiltshire (Martin's Hill; Martinsell)
Interior_Summary: Iron Age sherds, including fragments of haematite-coated bowls and stamped, incised and finger decorated wares and Roman sherds including 1st and 2nd century Samian and Savernake wares and some 3rd and 4th century fragments of ampulla, and part of red deer antler from rampart . Also coin of Cunobelin and Eppaticus nearby. Iron Age sherds found by Meyrick in quantity outside fort to W and NE and three Romano-British sherds just to W. Geophysical survey showed little internal activity (Payne et al 2006).
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Geophysical survey showed little internal activity (Payne et al 2006).

Interior_Summary: Quarry scoop behind rampart and many circular and curvilinear depressions possibly structures. Excavations by W.F. Grimes found Iron Age pottery in the primary fill of interior enclosure. 1804 Roman bronze spoon found. Roman pottery was also recorded by Colt Hoare.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Quarry scoop behind rampart. Much of N and W of interior densely settled and c.100 probable structures identified, surviving mainly as circular and curvilinear hollows or depressions c. 5m-10m diameter up to 0.6m deep.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavations by W.F. Grimes found Iron Age pottery in the primary fill of interior enclosure.

Interior_Summary: Little information as to what was found in excavation, but  possible odd sherds and quern stone. Roman and Saxon coins also found in vicinity. Neolithic long barrow excavated. Found two adult inhumations. Built in earthen tradition, with timber chamber at E end. Traces of side ditches visible.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavation of fine Neolithic long barrow on summit of hill found two adult inhumations. Built in earthen tradition, with timber chamber at E end. Traces of side ditches visible.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Hill, Blunsdon St Andrew, Wiltshire (Castle Hill, Swindon; Bury Blunsdon)
Interior_Summary: A number of probable storage pits were revealed during a magnetometer survey during 2004. Low earthworks within SW corner possible remains of occupation. Possible early Iron Age pottery found on S side of rampart.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Low earthworks within SW corner possible remains of occupation.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: A number of probable storage pits were revealed during a magnetometer survey during 2004.

Interior_Summary: Small 1988 excavation for building works found post-medieval layers only. LiDar survey found trackway (visible as raised linear bank) in NW quadrant to NW entrance. In SE quadrant two banks, but whether Iron Age or later unclear. Finds late Iron Age pottery, silver coin of Verica, bronze swords and decorated harness mount. Possible storage pits.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Small 1988 excavation for building works found post-medieval layers only.

Main_Display_Name: Fosbury Camp, Wiltshire (Haydon Hill Castle; Knoll Ditches; Knolls Down)
Interior_Summary: Quarry hollows along S side interior. Surface evidence of hollows in interior, 1m to 4m in diameter and up to 0.5m deep, possible pits and or hut platforms,as mapped by Ordnance Survey, but the geophysical survey showed little evidence apart from a few pits. Iron Age sherds, burnt flint, water-worn pebble (perhaps slingstone), sherd of pottery of fine sandy fabric.
Interior_Water_Comments: Pond at E extremity of hillfort.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Quarry hollows along S side interior. Surface evidence of hollows in interior, 1m to 4m in diameter and up to 0.5m deep, suggesting possible pits and or hut platforms as mapped by Ordnance Survey, but the geophysical survey showed little evidence apart from a few pits.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Surface evidence of hollows in interior, 1m to 4m in diameter and up to 0.5m deep, suggesting possible pits and or hut platforms as mapped by Ordnance Survey, but the geophysical survey showed little evidence apart from a few pits.

Interior_Summary: None.
None.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Rings, Donhead St Mary, Wiltshire
Interior_Summary: None.

Main_Display_Name: Winklebury Camp, Wiltshire (Winkelbury; Winterburgh; Winter Camp)
Interior_Summary: Pitt Rivers excavated six shallow depressions in turf of interior of fort and found to be Iron Age refuse pits. Basin shaped pit on E side surrounded by bank on the lower side was site of a hut with remains of timbering and wattle and daub. Pitt-Rivers made a mound near it with the excavated soil and thatched over the pit to preserve it. Pitt Rivers found early to middle Iron Age material and a few Romano-British finds. Number of flint implements or flakes, some underlying earliest defences. Late Bronze Age chisel-bladed tracer also found. Quarry hollows.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Indications of hut circles and pits are present within the interior. Quarry hollows.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Pitt Rivers excavated six shallow depressions in turf of interior of fort and found to be Iron Age refuse pits. Basin shaped pit on E side surrounded by bank on the lower side was site of a hut with remains of timbering and wattle and daub. Pitt-Rivers made a mound near it with the excavated soil and thatched over the pit to preserve it. He suggested depressions and pits to be 'pit dwellings'.

Main_Display_Name: White Sheet Castle, Wiltshire (Old Castle Hillfort; Whitesheet Hill; White Sheet Camp)
Interior_Summary: Sub-circular hollows and platforms within middle and outer bank to SE. For much of S and W circuit there is an internal quarry scoop.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Sub-circular hollows and platforms within middle and outer bank to SE. For much of S and W circuit there is an internal quarry scoop.

Interior_Summary: Aerial Photographs taken 1975-7 suggest that the possible annexe interior, between hillfort and strip lynchets to SE, contains many house platforms and pits. Internal quarry scoop immediately within hillfort interior.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Internal quarry scoop immediately within hillfort interior.

Interior_Summary: Slight ridge and furrow in interior on aerial photographs.
Excavations by Wainwright (1970) revealed a sub-rectangular post-built structure with hearth, other postholes and pits. Finds include pottery, metalwork, antler, bone and stone artefacts.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavations by Wainwright (1970) revealed a sub-rectangular post-built structure with hearth, other postholes and pits.

Main_Display_Name: Bury Wood Camp, Wiltshire (Bury Ditches; Bury Camp)
Interior_Summary: Quarry hollows. Small enclosure within interior visible on aerial photographs. Pottery, rotary and saddle querns, sling stones, loom weights, iron and bronze objects recovered from excavation. Also flint artefacts including scrapers, cores and flakes.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavation suggests pre-hillfort Iron Age occupation, two phases of rampart the first destroyed by fire, end of occupation c. 2nd century BC.

Interior_Summary: Geophysics (Payne et al 2006) shows between 20 and 50 roundhouses, 10m-15m diameter, in the N half of the hillfort arranged in lines. Possibly a later phase represented by a series of irregularly shaped ditched enclosures. Pits scattered across the whole site. Finds of haematite pottery.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Geophysics (Payne et al 2006) shows between 20 and 50 roundhouses, 10m-15m diameter, in the N half of the hillfort arranged in lines. Pits scattered across the whole site. Possible street-plan. Tracks.

Interior_Summary: Field system in interior. Possible house platforms and trackways, of uncertain date, incorporated into field system at NW side of fort. Neolithic perforated mace-head, two Roman coins hoards of AD 337 and AD 408, with part glass vessel, and six silver rings were found buried in two earthenware pots, in 1906 by S.W. Doughty while digging for stones on the line of the ramparts on NW brow of hill. Some in British Museum. Extensive aerial reconnaisance surveys by English Heritage.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Field system in interior. Possible house platforms and trackways, of uncertain date, incorporated into field system at NW side of fort.

Interior_Summary: Three postholes, possibly associated with the timber revetment, sealed beneath later layer of rampart material. Large pits backfilled with domestic rubbish.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Three postholes, possibly associated with the timber revetment, sealed beneath later layer of rampart material. Large pits backfilled with domestic rubbish.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Geophysical survey of mound. No details.

Interior_Summary: Excavation by R.C.C. Clay 1923 found no evidence of occupation. Iron Age pottery, spindle whorl or net sinker found outside hillfort. Coin of Constantine I found on site.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavation by R.C.C. Clay 1923 found no evidence of occupation.

Interior_Summary: Samian and Romano-British potsherds chance finds.

Main_Display_Name: Codford Circle, Wiltshire (Oldbury Camp; Wilsbury Ring; Woldsbury)
Interior_Summary: Air photographs taken in 2001 revealed an inner ditch, probably a palisade, running concentric to the earthwork and with clear opposing entrances to the E and W. Possible pit features in interior.
Quarry ditches inside the enclosure may indicate a former bank fallen into an outer ditch. AP investigation as part of English Heritage Quantocks AONB National Mapping Programme.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Quarry ditches inside the enclosure may indicate a former bank fallen into an outer ditch.

Main_Display_Name: Dowsborough Camp, Somerset (Dowsborough Castle Hill; Danesborough; Dawesbury)
Interior_Summary: A mound inside the NW entrance may be a barrow or a possible fire beacon site. A shallow round hollow may be evidence of charcoal burning and a post formally commemorated the coronation of George V. Mining trial pits in interior and these could explain the 6.6m x 3.6m hollow set behind the S rampart, although could be building. Possible WWII use. AP investigation as part of English Heritage Quantocks AONB National Mapping Programme.
Interior_Surface_Comments: A mound inside the NW entrance may be a round barrow or a possible fire beacon site. A shallow round hollow may be evidence of charcoal burning and a post formally commemorated the Coronation of George V. Mining trial pits in interior and these could explain the 6.6m by 3.6m hollow set behind the S rampart, although could be building.

Interior_Summary: Wartime cultivation unearthed worked flakes, cores and three leaf-shaped arrowheads. AP investigation Exmoor National Park National Mapping Programme - English Heritage. Deep pool in ditch to NE could possibly indicate a past water source.
Interior_Water_Comments: Deep pool in ditch to NE could possibly indicate a past water source.

Main_Display_Name: Clatworthy Camp, Somerset (Clatworthy Castle; Clatworthy Hillfort)
Interior_Summary: Quarry scoops behind the rampart on the N and W. AP investigation 1998 RCHME Brendon Hills Mapping Project.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Quarry scoops behind the rampart on the N and W.

Interior_Summary: None
Neolithic arrowhead and fragment of polished axe and Roman coins found.

Neolithic chipped flint axe, flakes and scrapers; hoard of Bronze Age bracelets, two palstaves and socketed axe from small V-shaped ditch under existing rampart; clay mould debris of late Bronze Age sword casting from pit at NE entrance; Iron Age and Roman-British pottery in quantity; iron slag suggests metalworking. Aerial photograph investigation 1989 and 1991 found evidence of interior features as cropmarks including at least five circular and sub-circular features c. 12-18m across - possible roundhouses; a sub-rectangular ditched enclosure just inside N rampart and numerous other linear and angled features. 100m to N field boundaries observed.
Interior_Water_Comments: Small valley to E of hillfort possible location of a spring.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Pits excavated and detail of ramparts determined, with no evidence of possible outer bank.

Interior_Summary: None other than stray finds, Neolithic and Roman.
Occupation layer contained Durotrigian pottery.
Only banks show on aerial photographs.

Main_Display_Name: Whitestaunton Camp, Somerset (Horse Pool Copse; Horse Pool Camp; Southay Camp; Harbury; Hamberry; Whitestanton Camp)
Interior_Summary: None
None

Main_Display_Name: Dundon Hill Camp, Somerset (Compton Dundon Hillfort)
Interior_Summary: No known true excavation of hillfort, apart from water pipe trench 1997 passing through NW rampart. Dundon Beacon mound 'excavated' 1827.Tin rings and Bronze Age pottery fragments from Dundon Beacon mound and animal bone and sherds of late Iron Age pottery from water pipe trench. Spring located in interior regards as a holy well in the medieval period.
Interior_Water_Comments: Spring located in interior regards as a holy well in the medieval period.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: No known true excavation of hillfort, apart from water pipe trench 1997. Dundon Beacon mound 'excavated' 1827.

Interior_Summary: Outer ditch appears to have acted as quarry source of rampart material.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Outer ditch appears to have acted as quarry source of rampart material.

Interior_Summary: Aerial photograph investigation 1990 proved promontory fort. A skeleton with an iron bracelet on the right arm, an iron knife, bone pin, two fibulae and a large quantity of Romano-British pottery were found. Magnetometer and resistivity surveys 1993 noted defences and interior features - roundhouses, pits, and linear features outside fort.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Magnetometer and resistivity surveys 1993 noted defences and interior features - roundhouses, pits, and linear features outside fort.

Interior_Summary: Excavations 1930 revealed closely grouped area of dwelling and storage pits of pre-Roman date. Geophysics over years found, for example, trackways, enclosures, ring ditches, pits and areas of industrial activity. Numerous finds including  late - probably Belgic - pit burial, pottery Halstatt form, Glastonbury type bowls, bead-rim vessels and other south-western type of Claudian conquest; bronze bulls-head of Celtic type (possibly ornamental chariot fitting); chariot horn caps; iron tyres of wheels; bridle-bits and nosebands. Iron currency bars, silvered bronze coins of Durotriges. Excavations 1930 revealed closely grouped area of dwelling and storage pits of pre-Roman date. Further occupation of Hamdon Hill during Roman period, including a villa in E interior at ST 41 NE 8. Miscellaneous finds of Saxon iron shield boss, and 14th century jug spout and bronze spur. Roman villa now being recognised from aerial photographs.
Interior_Water_Comments: No details, but possible source within.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Much quarrying may have masked any evidence.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Excavations 1930 revealed closely grouped area of dwelling and storage pits of pre-Roman date.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: Trackways, enclosures, ring ditches, pits and areas of industrial activity.

Interior_Summary: Roman pottery, gold coins and ring. Iron Age pottery.
None
Interior_Water_Comments: Possible spring located on side of hill.

Interior_Summary: Site visible on aerial photographs. Possible building platforms within, but could be associated with adjacent tile quarry.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Possible building platforms within, but could be associated with adjacent tile quarry.

Main_Display_Name: Cannington Park Camp, Somerset (Cynwit Castle; Cynuit Castle; Gynwir Castle; Kynwich Castle)
Interior_Summary: Neolithic, Bronze Age, Iron Age and Roman pottery finds. Iron Age brooch. Finds in Taunton Museum.
Interior_Surface_Comments: No definite hut sites in interior, but possible suitable rock terraces visible.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Various small excavations undertaken since 1905, but notably by P. Rahtz in 1963 who, because of Roman pottery as well as Iron Age finds and nearby cemetery, indicated later Roman reoccupation of the site.

Interior_Summary: 19th century excavation of dark occupation layer to W side of fort. RCAHME aerial surveys 1992-96- details not determined. 2004 geophysical surveys by S. Driscoll and S. Driscoll - details not determined. Evidence of Roman activity with building debris, coins, Samian and other sherds, charcoal and human remains. 18th/19th century reference to Roman coin hoard of Severus and Trajan and other Roman artefacts. Flint arrowhead. Later other Iron Age and and Romano-British pottery found. Three small post holes 2004 produced fragments of abraded Roman pottery, small fragments of bone, brick and burnt limestone.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: 19th century excavation of dark occupation layer to W side of fort.
Interior_Geophysics_Comments: 2004 geophysical surveys by S. Driscoll and S. Driscoll - details not determined.

Interior_Summary: Pillow mound and WWII slit trenches and pits. Aerial photograph interpretation - English Heritage Quantock Hills NMP - not determined.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Quarry hollows, pillow mound and WWII slit trenches and small pits.

Interior_Summary: Interior scarred by numerous trial pits for ironstone.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Interior scarred by numerous trial pits for ironstone.

Interior_Summary: Finds from trenches included butchered animal bone, early Iron Age pottery and Roman Savernake ware. Most of pottery abraded and local origin.
None
1998 geophysical survey - detail not determined.
Chance find of double-edged tanged knife. No details.
Interior_Water_Comments: Inner ditch to N often filled with water could indicate water source.

Interior_Summary: Site re-discovered by AP in 1961. Charcoal fragments were scattered through silt of both ditches found under the rampart. Three test pits dug in centre of interior found Mendip type flint tools, but no sign of occupation.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Trial pits dug in interior showed no sign of occupation.

Interior_Summary: Rotary quern found c. 1939-45 when overburden cleared from E end of site. Pot of Roman coins found 1691 - possibly Constantine.

Main_Display_Name: Small Down Camp, Somerset (Small Down Knoll Camp)
Interior_Summary: Excavated by H.St.G. Gray 1904 who found flint knife and scraper, a fragment of human jaw-bone and potsherds, later identified as Iron Age.

Various banks and mounds of local stone examined - their nature not determined. Numerous finds including pottery of Iron Age to Roman date, Romano-British brooches, currency bars, Roman coins, human bone and Roman burials and iron slag.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Inner quarry ditch. Various mounds and banks in evidence.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Various banks and mounds of local stone examined - their nature not determined.

Interior_Summary: None
None
Quarry scoops in interior; possible hut platforms.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Quarry scoops in interior; possible hut platforms.

Interior_Summary: None

Platforms for 125 timber built roundhouses.  In the E, a natural mound which has been artificially levelled, with an encircling ditch, considered to post-date the main period of excavation.  Timber and burning suggest it might have been a beacon. Pottery, metal and lithics found.
Interior_Water_Comments: A small stream rises about 300m to the S-E on the more accessible side.
Interior_Surface_Comments: A recent survey has identified 125 hut sites ranging in size from between 3-10m.  More might survive below ground and amongst quarry scoops. The majority are identifiable from a platform cut into the hillside. Several have ring-grooves visible.

Interior_Summary: No features contemporary with the hillfort have been identified
Interior_Surface_Comments: Enclosures within and outwith the enclosure are believed to relate to the use of the sheepfold

Interior_Summary: Nine roundhouse platforms are visible within the interior but no investigation has been carried out.   There is no known water source within the interior
Interior_Water_Comments: Streams lie in the valleys surrounding Great Hetha
Interior_Surface_Comments: Nine hut platforms have been identified

Interior_Summary: Circular stone foundations incorporating medium to large boulders, of at least eight buildings 4-8m in diameter with walls surviving up to 0.5m high. Two of the buildings have small areas of laid stone which are possibly hearths. A number of stone and earth banks form enclosures and sub-divisions within the interior of the settlement. At least two clearly defined scooped areas represent traces of earlier timber buildings.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Stone round-houses are probably Late Iron Age or Romano-British
Interior_Excavation_Comments: No record of excavation although possible trenches have been identified

Interior_Summary: House platforms and stone-founded hut circles 5-11m in diameter within the interior are believed to represent Iron Age and Romano-British occupation respectively.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Stone round-houses are probably Late Iron Age or Romano-British

Interior_Summary: No known internal features of Iron Age date. Romano-British settlement, medieval-post-medieval shielings, enclosures and rig and furrow
Interior_Surface_Comments: Overlying Late Iron Age or Romano-British settlement enclosure. The character of the round-houses is not specified, but they are likely to be stone founded (SH)

Interior_Summary: Rectilinear enclosure 52m by 37m, date and function unknown.  This is possibly the same feature shown on 1937-61 1:25,000 OS map and as Broom House on the 1885-1903 one-inch OS

The remains of at least seven stone-founded hut circles and low earthen banks forming internal divisions, some of which are interpreted as a later Romano-British phase of occupation. Also rectangular structures, probably medieval or post-medieval shielings.  Guard chambers were identified by Tate (1862) and MacLauchlan (1867). Range of finds from excavations including pottery, metal and animal bones.
Interior_Water_Comments: A spring was recorded by MacLauchlan (1867) 61m to the S of the hillfort
Interior_Surface_Comments: Stone founded and earthen walls. Stone round-houses are probably Late Iron Age or Romano-British. Rectangular structures are probably later shielings

Interior_Summary: No features recorded

Main_Display_Name: Glead's Cleugh Camp, Northumberland (Gledes-Cleugh Camp; Gleadscleugh)
Interior_Summary: Fourteen scooped house platforms have been identified within the enclosure along terraces lying either side of a terraced trackway. The lack of building stone suggests the platforms are Iron Age, possibly for timber-built roundhouses
Interior_Water_Comments: A stream originates from a spring in the NE corner

Main_Display_Name: Humbleton Hill Camp, Northumberland (Homildon; Hameldun; Holmedon; Homilheugh)
Interior_Summary: Up to eight circular house platforms lie between the inner and outer ramparts with a further 20 within the inner rampart.  They vary in size between 4m and 8m in diameter and are often terraced into the hillslope. Oblique aerial photographs also reveal traces of ring-ditch or ring-groove houses in the large outer enclosure (SH)

The remains of three turf covered hut circles between 7m and 8m in diameter internally with walls standing up to 0.2m high.  Two have entrances approximately 2m wide on the N and NE sides. A rectangular building 6m by 19m and up to 0.1m high lies near the entrance in the W.
Interior_Water_Comments: The entrance to the SE gives access to a small valley which leads to a spring and small stream to the E.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Stone round-houses are probably Late Iron Age or Romano-British. Rectangular structures are probably later

Interior_Summary: Three circular stone huts are possibly contemporary with the hillfort. An enclosed settlement within the hillfort considered to be Romano-British in date, survives as at least four small enclosures, one with evidence for two definite and two possible circular building platforms. The other is possibly a stock enclosure
Interior_Surface_Comments: Stone round-houses are probably Late Iron Age or Romano-British

Interior_Summary: Internal divisions, possibly the remains of yards, visible as low stone banks and three shallow depressions with stone walling represent the remains of houses. These range in size from 4.5-8.5 m in diameter.  A further ring bank 6m in diameter overlies the inner rampart. A rectangular building platform survives as an L-shaped bank 0.2m high and 2.5m wide. All are considered to be later than the enclosing works
Interior_Water_Comments: Mere Burn lies a few metres to the E
Interior_Surface_Comments: Internal divisions and stone round-houses are probably Late Iron Age or Romano-British

Interior_Summary: Two hut circles lie at the E and W extremities of the site 4.0m and 7.0m in diameter respectively.
Interior_Surface_Comments: Stone round-houses are probably Late Iron Age or Romano-British

Interior_Summary: No internal features are recorded
Interior_Water_Comments: Lies to the E of the confluence of the Waren and Chuckbridge Burns.

Interior_Summary: Cropmark of two concentric ditches, no further investigation is known
Timber and stone round-houses

Main_Display_Name: Castle Dykes, Dunglass Dean, Scottish Borders (Castle Dykes, Dunglass Mill)
Interior_Summary: Featureless apart from short arc of ditch on N cliff edge.
Foundations of stone structures said to have been ploughed up.
Featureless apart from the remains of the overlying medieval castle
Featureless

Main_Display_Name: Gallow Law, Northumberland (Clennell Street; Castle Hills)
Interior_Summary: No evidence for occupation contemporary with the hillfort.  The foundations of a rectangular structure in the centre of the enclosure is possibly later.  Unconfirmed report of 'guard posts' near to the entrance in the E

Interior_Summary: Internally a double stone wall divided the larger enclosure into two compartments with the one in the NW enclosing approximately 0.64ha and in the SE 0.31ha. Excavations of  nine of the huts in 1924-5 (Ball 1927) produced quernstones, whetstones, a cup marked stone and a piece of medieval pottery.  The SE appears to have been uninhabited

Interior_Summary: A number of hut circles have been recorded within the interior. Two constructed of timber walls set in irregular stone-filled trenches 9m and 10m in diameter, were excavated by Burgess (1984). An extensive sunken cobbled surface near the centre of the enclosure edged by postholes 1.5m apart along its curved margin, was also recorded. Finds recovered during the excavations included sherds of coarse handmade and decorated pottery and a flint blade.

The foundations of a rectangular building, probably modern, which has cut into the inner rampart, lies in the E. Range of material culture from excavations.

Suggested possible leather lined channel to pit 1.5m deep leading from spring hollow (Wailes 1963, 54) to catch water.

Interior_Summary: Excavations in 1968-70 by Douch and Beard and earlier geophysics found a possibly pre-Roman circular building and pattern of sub-rectangular enclosures in interior. Finds from trench just inside E defences included coins, brooches, glass and pottery, all, apart from a few Iron Age sherds, 1st century to second half of 3rd century AD (most 60-130 AD). Iron slag associated with smithy. Excavations in the NW corner of the camp revealed post-holes of a timber tower.

Interior_Summary: Interior contained four-to six-post structures (c. 20) and roundhouse remains, defined by postholes indicating complex building sequence with frequent replacements of structures over a prolonged period. Two oval structures possibly Romano-British or later occupation, although pottery assemblage suggests abandonment before Roman period. South-Western decorated pottery and cordoned wares, late Iron Age bead and amphorae found. Iron Age imported glass bracelets and a glass bead.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Interior contained c. 20 four- to six-post structures and round houses remains, defined by post holes indicating complex building sequence with frequent replacements of structures over a prolonged period. Two oval structures possibly Romano-British or later occupation, although pottery assemblage suggests abandonment before Roman period.

Interior_Summary: Inner ditch and rampart sectioned, ditch being cut 2.8m into bedrock with primary silt at base. Inner rampart, probably at least two phases, survived only as 0.2m thick disturbed layer of soil and shillet sealing beneath it, in the old land surface, pit containing charcoal. Trial strip between two ramparts produced curved gullies not found in interior. Excavations of 210 sq.m adjacent to ploughed down S inner rampart revealed long sequence of timber buildings, including four-post structures and a seven post framed for the ring beam of a 9m diameter round house. In old land surface, pit containing charcoal. Excavations 1974-76 produced Cornish La Tene decorated pottery (Glastonbury Ware) associated with all structural phases, with a little Cordoned Ware from latter levels. All this material for pottery originated from the Lizard. Amphora also. Plant remains and pollen. Slag indicating metal working.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Inner ditch and rampart sectioned, ditch being cut 2.8m into bedrock with primary silt at base. Inner rampart, probably at least two phases, survived only as 0.2m thick disturbed layer of soil and shillet sealing beneath it, in the old land surface, pit containing charcoal. Trial strip between two ramparts produced curved gullies not found in interior. Excavations of 210 sq.m adjacent to ploughed down S inner rampart revealed long sequence of timber buildings, including four-post structures and a seven post framed for the ring beam of a 9m diameter round house.

Interior_Summary: Thought interior divided into a ring of buildings with large furnace, around an open space, but very little of the walls remains. 1925 excavation found lthis large furnace in N of enclosure with 3.7m deep well in NNW, cleared out c. 25 years previously, a house of elliptical form E of the well and another in SE quadrant with two chambers. Finds included pottery, muller, slingstones, flint chips, 3 spindle whorls, a portion of shale bracelet, iron and tin slag. 1927 and 1930 excavations proved that the septa, first shown on Borlase's plan, and still extant, later than castle and may be cattle pens erected date unknown. Four earlier buildings found between N side of inner gate and E side of well. Finds included hammer-stones, flint flake,glass fragments and pottery.
Interior_Excavation_Comments: Thought interior divided into a ring of buildings with large furnace, around an open space, but very little of walls remain. 1925 excavation found of this large furnace in N of enclosure with 3.7m deep well in NNW, cleared out c. 25 years previously, house of elliptical form E of the well and another in SE quadrant with two chambers. 1927 and 1930 excavations proved that the septa, first shown on Borlase's plan, and still extant, later than castle and may be cattle pens erected date unknown. Four earlier buildings found between N side of inner gate and E side of well.

Interior_Summary: Excavation found spindle whorls, ground stone hammer or mace head, flint, nodules of iron pyrites and sea pebbles. They measure 22m in diameter and 0.9m high, and 27m NNW-SSE by 20m WSW-ENE and 1.3m high, respectively. The N barrow partly truncated on ENE by field boundary bank.
